{"id":"2011.07228","submitter":"Noboru Ito","authors":"Noboru Ito and Yusuke Takimura","title":"Strong and weak (1, 2) homotopies on knot projections and new invariants","comments":"15 pages, 20 figures","journal-ref":"Kobe J. Math. 33 (2016), 13--30","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Every second flat Reidemeister move of knot projections can be decomposed\ninto two types thorough an inverse or direct self-tangency modification,\nrespectively called strong or weak, when orientations of the knot projections\nare arbitrarily provided. Further, we introduce the notions of strong and weak\n(1, 2) homotopies; we define that two knot projections are strongly (resp.\nweakly) (1, 2) homotopic if and only if two knot projections are related by a\nfinite sequence of first and strong (resp. weak) second flat Reidemeister\nmoves. This paper gives a new necessary and sufficient condition that two knot\nprojections are not strongly (1, 2) homotopic. Similarly, we obtain a new\nnecessary and sufficient condition in the weak (1, 2) homotopy case. We also\ndefine a new integer-valued strong (1, 2) homotopy invariant. Using it, we show\nthat the set of the non-trivial prime knot projections without 1-gons that can\nbe trivialized under strong (1, 2) homotopy is disjoint from that of weak (1,\n2) homotopy. We also investigate topological properties of the new invariant\nand give its generalization, a comparison of our invariants and Arnold\ninvariants, and a table of invariants.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 14 Nov 2020 06:42:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-11-17"}
